<br>
ISP is the propulsion engineer’s way of assessing how effectively propellant is being used. ISP stands for Specific Impulse. The ISP number is the number of pounds of thrust you get for each pound of propellant consumed per second (so its unit is in seconds, it is also closely related to the velocity at which propellant is ejected).<br>
<br>
With conventional chemical rockets the best you can get is an ISP of about 450<br>
<br>
The fact that conventional propulsion systems involve the combustion of the propellant means that it is easy to lose track of what is actually happening. Propulsion works by using a source of energy to accelerate a propellant to a high velocity and a mechanism that then ejects it in a manner that drives the spaceship forward.<br>
<br>
With a chemical propellant the energy source and the propellant are combined. The combustion of the fuel provides the energy to heat the combustion products to a high temperature, which are then ejected from the motor as propellant. There is a limit as to how hot a chemical reaction will go and that is what, effectively, limits the ISP to only 450. If you want a higher ISP, you need higher ejection velocities, which means higher temperature.<br>
<br>
To get an ISP of more than 450 we need to separate the energy source from the propellant.<br>
<br>
The next stage up from a chemical rocket is to feed the propellant (typically Liquid Hydrogen) through the core of a ceramic based nuclear reactor. This can give an ISP of about 900, on the face of it quite a respectable improvement. However when you consider that nuclear reactions deliver about a million times as much energy as chemical ones, merely doubling the ISP seems rather disappointing. The problem is down to temperature. Despite the fact that vast amounts of energy are available from nuclear reactions, the temperature (and thus the ISP) is limited by the melting point of the materials used to build the reactor. Even with ceramics a maximum of only about 2,500 k is possible. Which is only twice the temperature of a chemical engine.<br>
<br>
To get higher ISPs than this we need an altogether different approach. We need an electric engine. There are many different designs for electric propulsion systems but, in essence, they all do the same thing. They use electric and/or magnetic fields to accelerate the propellant to very high velocities, anywhere up to 300Km/s (which gives an ISP of around 30,000). This is a really useful improvement but it comes with a severe penalty! <br>
<br>
The problem with electric drives is that they are only capable of delivering tiny thrusts and therefore very low accelerations. This is fine once you are already in space and provided you aren’t in any hurry, a high ISP electric drive operating at 1/100th of a g for weeks or even months can build up a lot of speed. They are however completely incapable of launching a spaceship from the earth. One could be forgiven for thinking that this limitation is down to the current state of the engineering art and that, somehow, improvements will be made in the future to deliver the Holy Grail of high ISP and high thrust simultaneously. This isn’t going to happen!! The problem isn’t to do with engineering; it's to do with power!<br>
<br>
The increase in ISP is proportional to the increase in exhaust velocity but the amount of energy that you need to do this is proportional to the square of the increase in velocity (e.g. To double the exhaust velocity takes 4 times as much energy). To increase the ISP from 450 to 30,000 or 64 times takes 64^2 as much energy per pound (around 4000 times as much) now, of course, each pound of propellant is doing 64 times as much work so we only need 1/64th as much propellant/second and therefore we only need 64 times as much power to get the same thrust as a chemical engine but that is still a lot of power!<br>
<br>
Lets be quite clear about this. Not even in our wildest science fiction fantasies will we ever be able to generate, channel, and control the amount of electrical energy necessary for a high thrust, high ISP, electric drive.<br>
<br>
To Illustrate. The main engines on the Saturn 5 generate around 120 Gw (Source NASA), to get the same thrust from a high ISP electric drive would need at least 70 times as much power That’s 8,500Gwe! Probably more than the entire global electrical generating capacity, to be generated and controlled ON BOARD THE SPACESHIP!  <br>
<br>
This is not to say however that the Holy Grail is unattainable, it’s just that we need a different approach yet again.<br>
<br>
Firstly we need to accept that only nuclear processes (Fission and/or Fusion) are capable of generating power on this scale (unless we find a way of tapping zero point energy, if that happens everything changes! J )<br>
<br>
Secondly we have to accept that at the power levels we are considering we are consuming fission and/or Fusion fuel at a rate of Kilos per second, tens of thousands of times the consumption rate of any power station. At these power levels we are not going to be able to operate any sort of contained, continuous process like a power reactor nor are we going to be able to convert the nuclear energy into electricity for an electric drive. Instead we need to find a way of using the energy more or less directly and in a way that doesn’t vaporise the space ship.<br>
<br>
The first trick is to do the reactions outside the spaceship without even trying to contain the heat, the second is to generate the thrust in pulses rather than continuously so that the average heat is low enough for the spaceship to tolerate. A good analogy is a car engine, the combustion temperature of the fuel/air mixture is well above the melting point of the materials that the engine is made out of, but because the power comes in short duration pulses, the motor can operate without melting.<br>
<br>
Its called Nuclear Pulse Propulsion (or NPP) and it is the Only technology we have that is capable of produceing high ISP and high thrust at the same time, with NPP it is possible to get ISP’s into the ten’s of thousands (or more) and thrusts powerful enough to earth launch ships weighing hundreds of thousands or even millions of tons.<br>
<br>
Unless we embrace NPP we will never be able to put the millions of tons of material into orbit that will be necessary to enable self-sustaining communities to develop.<br>
